T1  - When Does Predation Dominate Collusion?
AU  - Wiseman, Thomas
Y1  - 2017/03/01
PY  - 2017
DA  - 2017/03/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA13121
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 555
EP  - 584
VL  - 85
IS  - 2
KW  - Dynamic games
KW  - collusion
KW  - exit
KW  - bankruptcy
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA13121
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - I study repeated competition among oligopolists. The only novelty is that firms may go bankrupt and permanently exit: the probability that a firm survives a price war depends on its financial strength, which varies stochastically over time. Under some conditions including no entry, an anti-folk theorem holds: when firms are patient, so that strength levels change relatively quickly, every Nash equilibrium involves an immediate price war that lasts until at most one firm remains. Surprisingly, the possibility of entry may facilitate collusion, as may impatience. The model can explain some observed patterns of collusion and predation.
ER  - 

